Section 1. Introduction¶

About the dataset used in this data analysis:¶

Given information about the dataset:

  • This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

  • Certain columns, like ‘cast’ and ‘genres’, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters.

  • There are some odd characters in the ‘cast’ column. Don’t worry about cleaning them. You can leave them as is.
  • The final two columns ending with “_adj” show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

Preliminary Issues with the given dataset, after checking the CSV file:¶

  • Revenue and Budget have no currency unit, but since the data is about US based movies, I'll assume it's in USD.

  • Popularity is gauge of the movie's popularity, but I'm not sure how is it calculated. It's not mentioned anywhere, but I found some articles about it here, here and here!

  • Pipe seperators for some columns

  • Several columns such as cast, production companies and genres are grouped in a single entry seperated by "|" so I'll fix that by divining them into seperate columns or unpack them in a seperate dfs, I'll see how it'll go

  • Id, IMDB_ID, homepage seem useless is our data analysis, they'll be dropped

  • I'll adjust the revneue_adj and budget_adj to 2021, by using this inflation tool, I found online, I'll adjust it by multiplying by 1.2076

  • I'll inspect the data further as a DataFrame and check for further issues

The questions I'll look to answer with my analysis:¶


  • Question 1: Is there a specific day and month where movie makers like to release their movies? What's the year with the highest movie releases?

  • Question 2: What's the correlation (if any) between the movie's revenue and it's popularity and it's popularity vs the audience vote count?

  • Question 3: What's the average movie runtime? What are the top 5 longest movies and how does runtime distribution look like?

  • Question 4: What's the highest revenue movie made and is it the same is the most popular movie vs the movie with the highest vote count?

  • Question 5: Are we spending more money on making movies over the last years? If yes, are we making more money as well?

  • Question 6: What genres of movies are released the most? Which keywords are used in describing movies?

  • Question 7: What's the year to recommend to watch the movies released during?

  • Question 8: What are the Top 10 highest-revenue movies? By whom were they directed? And what genres do they belong to?

  • Question 9: What are the Top 10 production companies in terms of movie releases?

  • Question 10: Who are the Top 10 casted actors in the movies?

  • Question 11: Who are the Top 10 directors with most movie releases? Who were the directors of the higest revenue movies? Question 11.2: Who were the directors of the most popular movies?

C.1 Create the function for splitting the main df columns into seperate dataframes and outputting a dataframe with values in seperate columns¶

In [47]:
# Define a function to seperate and rename columns into new subsetted dataframes
def cols_make(dfcolumn):
    """
    Expands a single column in a dataframe with a delimiter, in this case it's pipe '|'
    Args: 
        (dfcolumn) The dataframe column which you want to split values in a single column into a new dataframe with 
         multiple columns
    Returns:
        A dataframe of seperated columns of the values, with renames column names
    """
    return dfcolumn.str[0:].str.split('|',expand = True)

#run the function on the desired columns
df_cast = cols_make(df.cast).rename(columns = lambda x: f"cast_{x+1}")
df_genres = cols_make(df.genres).rename(columns = lambda x: f"genres_{x+1}")
df_keywords = cols_make(df.keywords).rename(columns = lambda x: f"keywords_{x+1}")
df_prod_companies = cols_make(df.production_companies).rename(columns = lambda x: f"prod_comp_{x+1}")
df_director = cols_make(df.director).rename(columns = lambda x: f"director_{x+1}")

C.2 The function for melting and counting the values of the cast, genre, keyword and production company and outputing a pd.Series¶

In [49]:
# Define a function to melt all columns, count each value occurence and return a pd.Series
def col_stacker(df):
    """
    Creates a a single-column series from a given dataframes with columns, counts it's values and sorts it
    Args:
        (df) The dataframe which you want to combine all columns into a single column
    Returns:
        A single column of values, counted and sorted as a pd.series
    """
    return df.melt()['value'].value_counts(sort=True)

#run the function on the desired columns
actors_series = col_stacker(df_cast)
genres_series = col_stacker(df_genres)
keywords_series = col_stacker(df_keywords)
prod_comp_series = col_stacker(df_prod_companies)
directors_series = col_stacker(df_director)

To better visualize genres and keywords, I created a word cloud function to call it since I'll be using it multiple times for the genres and keywords.

In [72]:
def cloud_maker(words, w, h, bg_col, wh):
    """
    Creates a word cloud for a given series or frequency list, in this case it's a value counts output

    Args:
        (int) words - pd Series containing the value counts of the words
        (int) w,h - are the width and hieght respectively, don't confuse with figsize
        (str) bg_col - choice of background color
        (str) wh - the number of rows to display i.e. the head of the value counts, it determines how crowded the word cloud will be
    Returns:
        cloud_img - word cloud for the chosen word list and parameters
    """
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,8))
    cloud_img = WordCloud(width=w, height=h, background_color= bg_col).generate_from_frequencies(words.head(wh))
    plt.imshow(cloud_img)
    plt.axis("off")
    return (cloud_img);

Section 4: Conclusions¶

  • The highest year for movie released was 2014, while the highest month was September. The highest day was Friday.
  • There is a slight positive correlation between revenue and vote count vs popularity.
  • The distribution of the runtime seems to be skewed to the right, around 50% of the movies have a runtime of 100 minute, although 75% of the movies had a running time of 113 minutes.
  • The movie with the highest revenue is "2009's Avatar" but the one with highest popularity is "2015's Jurassic World" and the one with the highest vote count is "2010's Inception". The answer is no, so the most profitable movie doesn't mean it's the most popular one and also it's not the move voted for.
  • The movie industry has been growing steadily in the last decades, from the plot above, it's visible that more revenue is generated yearly from movies than before.Also the budget we spend on movie has increased over the last decades.
  • The top 5 Genres of movies released are Drama, Comedy, Thriller, Action and, Romance.
  • According to popularity, the year 2015 seems to be a good year for binging on movies!
  • I'd recommend watching these 2 movies of 2015:

    2015's Jurassic World with a popularity rating of 32.99 2015's Mad Max: Fury Road with a popularity rating of 28.42

  • According to vote average of viewers, based on the vote average, the year 1973 seems to be a good year for catching a good movie. The highest vote average was for the year 2006. Check out Pink Floyd:Pulse.
  • The top 10 production companies in terms of number of movies released are, in descending order: Warner Bros. , Universal Pictures, Paramount Pictures, Twentieth Century Fox Film Corporation, Columbia Pictures, New Line Cinema, Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer (MGM), Walt Disney Pictures, Touchstone Pictures And Columbia Pictures Corporation.
  • The top 10 casted actors, in descedning order are Robert De Niro, Samuel L. Jackson, Bruce Willis, Nicolas Cage, Michael Caine, Robin Williams, John Goodman, Morgan Freeman, John Cusack and Tom Hanks.
  • The top 10 directors with most movies released, in descending order, are: Woody Allen, Clint Eastwood,Steven Spielberg, Martin Scorsese, Ridley Scott, Ron Howard, Steven Soderbergh, Joel Schumacher and David Cronenberg.

Limitations in the Analyzed Dataset¶

Limitation 1: When I did this analysis, I purposely chose to remove the unused columns first thing in the data cleaning process because when I tried to remove them at the end, I ended up with less than 2000 rows of usable data. This is due to the fact that the homepage column has 2936 non-null values, so when I preformed dropping the null values, it removed many of the usable data rows. I'll stick to remove the unused columns first as intially planned. The limitation here being that the dataset has incomplete data, and the question that begs to be answered, is the data realiable to make solid conclusions or not.
Limitation 2: The runtime column had very small values (i.e. 3 mins) and very large ones( i.e. 705 minutes) so I decided to look at the data closely and searched some of the titles with short and long runtime. I noticed that the movies and mini TV series info is mixed in the TMDB csv file meaning there is no way to differenitate between them in the given date, the main clue would be the long runtime, but then again if it's not clearly defined most probably it will be confusing. Additionally, this creates a problem with the analysis output since they are different categories of shows.

Limitation 3: When I checked the revenue_adj and budget_adj columns, there were a lot of zero values. So I checked a random movie Survivor and the budget number is on point but the revenue is zero which is off and it says on the wikipedia page it made in box office $3,839,100 so I'll dropped them. This meant I'm dropped around half of the original values for the df which are due to the zero values in budget_adj and revnue_adj, which might affect my EDA for budgetary and revenue analysis! Again the limitation being there are alot of these values either missing or input incorrectly.

Limitation 4: When I ran the analysis with the main df and dropped the budget and revenue zero values, it changed the release year mode from 2014 to 2011, which might mean that removing all those rows with zero budget and revenue impacted our findings in a big way. This boils down to the data not being reliable enough or inconsistent. One work around is take the release year and original title to make a mini df to get more accurate results or seperate the financial related columns in one as I did in my analysis
